et of beliefs about the Bible, the book raises serious questions about the trade in biblical antiquities, the integrity of academic research, and the place of private belief in public life.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Mrz 2022) 0aChristianity and culturezUnited States. 0aChristianityxInfluence. 0aEvangelicalismzUnited States. 7aRELIGION / Christianity / Protestant.2bisacsh  aAcademic freedom.  aAmericans.  aArchaeology.  aAuction.  aBaptists.  aBasic Books.  aBible society.  aBible.  aBiblical canon.  aBiblical criticism.  aBiblical inerrancy.  aBiblical law.  aBiblical manuscript.  aBillionaire.  aBusiness ethics.  aCatholic Church.  aCatholicism.  aChristian Church.  aChristian apologetics.  aChristian mission.  aChristian school.  aChristian.  aChristianity.  aCouncil for Christian Colleges and Universities.  aCredential.  aCredibility.  aCurator.  aCurriculum.  aDavid Trobisch.  aDead Sea Scrolls.  aDue diligence.  aDwight L. Moody.  aEBay.  aEmployment.  aEvangelicalism.  aFocus on the Family.  aForay.  aForgery.  aGenerosity.  aGeorge Marsden.  aGod.  aGospel of Judas.  aGrand Canyon University.  aGreen Collection.  aHebrew Bible.  aHistoricity of the Bible.  aHobby Lobby.  aIndiana Wesleyan University.  aInstitution.  aJerry Falwell.  aJews.  aJohn Templeton Foundation.  aJudaism.  aKen Ham.  aLecture.  aLiterature.  aMark Noll.  aMart Green.  aMis"ing Jesus.  aMuseum of the Bible.  aNarrative.  aNew Testament.  aOf Education.  aOld Testament.  aOwnership.  aOxford University Press.  aPapyrology.  aPastor.  aPatriotism.  aPentecostalism.  aPhilanthropy.  aPrinceton University Press.  aPrivatization.  aProsperity theology.  aProtestantism.  aProvenance.  aPubli